Here, your brother called.

40
00:02:13,381 --> 00:02:15,205
Roz, in the trade we call that "avoidance".

41
00:02:15,206 --> 00:02:17,326
Don't change the subject, tell me what you think.

42
00:02:17,427 --> 00:02:19,292
Did I ever tell you what this little button does?

43
00:02:20,043 --> 00:02:22,154
I am not a piece of Lalique.

44
00:02:22,155 --> 00:02:23,554
I can handle criticism.

45
00:02:23,555 --> 00:02:24,876
How was I today?

46
00:02:25,239 --> 00:02:26,232
Let's see...

47
00:02:27,141 --> 00:02:28,341
you dropped two commercials

48
00:02:28,342 --> 00:02:30,751
you left a total of twenty-eight seconds of dead air,

49
00:02:30,752 --> 00:02:32,677
you scrambled the station's call letters,

50
00:02:32,678 --> 00:02:33,988
you spilled yogurt on the control board,

51
00:02:33,989 --> 00:02:35,299
and you kept referring to Jerry,

52
00:02:35,300 --> 00:02:36,617
with the identity crisis

53
00:02:36,618 --> 00:02:37,800
as "Jeff".

54
00:02:43,795 --> 00:02:45,437
- You say my brother called...
- Mmm, hmm

55
00:02:51,097 --> 00:02:52,030
So I said to the gardener

56
00:02:52,031 --> 00:02:55,222
"Yoshi, I do not want a Zen garden in my backyard.

57
00:02:55,658 --> 00:02:58,269
If I want to rake gravel every ten minutes to maintain my inner harmony,

58
00:02:58,270 --> 00:02:59,476
I'll move to Yokohama."

59
00:03:01,437 --> 00:03:05,278
Well, this offends him, so he starts pulling up  Maris' prized Camellias by the handful.

60
00:03:05,279 --> 00:03:06,780
Well, I coundn't stand for that,

61
00:03:06,781 --> 00:03:10,736
so I marched right into the morning room and locked the door until he cooled down.

62
00:03:13,458 --> 00:03:15,362
Tell me you would have handled it differently, Frasier.

63
00:03:16,857 --> 00:03:17,846
Oh, I'm sorry, Niles

64
00:03:17,847 --> 00:03:19,407
I didn't realise you'd stopped talking

65
00:03:20,876 --> 00:03:22,458
You haven't heard a word I said.

66
00:03:22,459 --> 00:03:23,667
Oh Niles, you're a psychiatrist

67
00:03:23,668 --> 00:03:27,466
you know what it's like to listen to people prattling on endlessly about their mundane lives.

68
00:03:28,183 --> 00:03:28,949
Touché

69
00:03:29,358 --> 00:03:31,400
And on that subject, I heard your show today.

70
00:03:37,631 --> 00:03:38,753
And?

71
00:03:38,754 --> 00:03:40,687
You know what I think about pop psychiatry

72
00:03:40,687 --> 00:03:42,409
Yes, I know what you think about everything.

73
00:03:43,015 --> 00:03:45,547
When was the last time you had an unexpressed thought?

74
00:03:45,548 --> 00:03:46,548
I'm having one now.

75
00:03:48,980 --> 00:03:51,838
- You guys ready?
- Two café latte supremos

76
00:04:00,549 --> 00:04:01,326
No, thank you

77
00:04:03,923 --> 00:04:06,810
So, Frasier, How are you doing on your own?

78
00:04:07,790 --> 00:04:08,929
I'm fine.

79
00:04:09,634 --> 00:04:10,755
I love my new life.

80
00:04:11,249 --> 00:04:12,795
I love the solitude.

81
00:04:13,051 --> 00:04:14,644
I miss Frederick like the dickens, of course.

82
00:04:15,119 --> 00:04:16,042
You know, he's quite a boy.

83
00:04:16,043 --> 00:04:19,189
He's playing goalie on the peewee soccer team now.

84
00:04:19,190 --> 00:04:20,887
Ha, he's a chip off the old block!

85
00:04:22,163 --> 00:04:23,793
- You hated sports.
- So does he!

86
00:04:26,682 --> 00:04:28,212
The fresh air's good for him.

87
00:04:29,527 --> 00:04:31,644
Oh well, this has been fun, Frasier, but...

88
00:04:33,145 --> 00:04:35,376
we have a problem, and that's why I thought we should talk.

89
00:04:35,644 --> 00:04:36,669
Is it Dad?

90
00:04:36,670 --> 00:04:37,389
Afraid so.

91
00:04:37,390 --> 00:04:40,409
One of his buddies from the police force called this morning.

92
00:04:40,410 --> 00:04:43,071
He went over to see him, and found him on the bathroom floor.

93
00:04:43,072 --> 00:04:45,082
- Oh, my God!
- No, it's okay, he's fine.

94
00:04:45,540 --> 00:04:47,000
What, his hip again?

95
00:04:47,927 --> 00:04:50,450
Frasier, I don't think he can live alone anymore.

96
00:04:52,098 --> 00:04:53,077
What can we do?

97
00:04:53,763 --> 00:04:56,957
Well, I know this isn't going to be anyone's favourite solution,

98
00:04:56,958 --> 00:05:01,225
but I took the liberty of checking out a few convalescent homes for him.

99
00:05:01,226 --> 00:05:03,787
Oh Niles, a home? He's still a young man!

100
00:05:03,788 --> 00:05:06,075
Well, you certainly can't take care of him

101
00:05:06,076 --> 00:05:07,756
you're just getting your new life together.

102
00:05:07,757 --> 00:05:11,052
Absolutely. Besides, we were never simpatico.

103
00:05:11,701 --> 00:05:13,576
Of course, I can't take care of him.

104
00:05:13,577 --> 00:05:15,027
Oh yes, yes, of course, of course...

105
00:05:15,679 --> 00:05:16,590
Why?

106
00:05:18,146 --> 00:05:19,678
Because dad doesn't get along with Maris.

107
00:05:19,679 --> 00:05:20,663
Who does?

108
00:05:21,860 --> 00:05:23,547
I thought you liked my Maris!

109
00:05:23,928 --> 00:05:25,204
I do. I...

110
00:05:25,205 --> 00:05:26,871
I like her from a distance.

111
00:05:27,403 --> 00:05:28,892
You know, the way you like the sun.

112
00:05:29,162 --> 00:05:30,311
Maris is like the sun.

113
00:05:30,994 --> 00:05:32,270
Except without the warmth.

114
00:05:37,356 --> 00:05:40,019
Well, then, we're agreed about what to do with dad.

115
00:05:41,483 --> 00:05:44,939
"Golden Acres: We Care So You Don't Have To."

116
00:05:50,823 --> 00:05:51,998
It says that?

117
00:05:51,999 --> 00:05:53,216
Well, it might as well!

118
00:05:56,049 --> 00:05:58,182
Alright, I'll make up the spare bedroom.

119
00:05:58,183 --> 00:06:01,606
Oh, you're a good son, Frasier.

120
00:06:02,696 --> 00:06:05,480
Two café supremos. Anything to eat?

121
00:06:05,948 --> 00:06:08,015
No. I seem to have lost my appetite.

122
00:06:08,561 --> 00:06:10,266
I'll have a large piece of cheesecake!

123
00:06:45,080 --> 00:06:48,768
- Hi!
- We finally made it!

124
00:06:48,769 --> 00:06:52,048
Ah, dad, dad, welcome to your new home!

125
00:06:53,190 --> 00:06:54,405
Gee, you look great!

126
00:06:54,406 --> 00:06:56,650
Don't B. S. me, I do not look great.

127
00:06:57,189 --> 00:06:59,041
I spent Monday on the bathroom floor.

128
00:06:59,042 --> 00:07:01,687
You can still se the tile marks on my face.

129
00:07:03,328 --> 00:07:05,549
Gives you some idea about the ride over in the car.

130
00:07:06,889 --> 00:07:08,802
Well, er, here we are...

131
00:07:09,668 --> 00:07:13,852
Rest assured the refrigerator is stocked with your favourite beer, Ballantines.

132
00:07:14,070 --> 00:07:17,167
- and we've got plenty of hot links and coleslaw...
- Mmm!

133
00:07:17,281 --> 00:07:19,944
And I just rented a Charles Bronson movie for later!

134
00:07:19,945 --> 00:07:22,010
Let's cut the "Welcome To Camp Crane" speech.

135
00:07:22,011 --> 00:07:23,151
We all know why I'm here.

136
00:07:23,152 --> 00:07:26,191
Your old man can't be left alone for ten minutes without falling on his ass

137
00:07:26,192 --> 00:07:28,297
and Frasier got stuck with me.
Isn't that right?

138
00:07:28,998 --> 00:07:31,104
- No, no!
- No, no!

139
00:07:32,694 --> 00:07:35,876
I want you here! It'll give us a chance to get reacquainted!

140
00:07:35,877 --> 00:07:38,015
That implies we were acquainted at one point.

141
00:07:43,464 --> 00:07:45,625
Well, listen,

142
00:07:46,188 --> 00:07:48,565
why don't I take dad's things into his new bachelor quarters

143
00:07:48,566 --> 00:07:51,246
so you two scoundrels can plan some hijinks!

144
00:07:53,870 --> 00:07:55,964
I think that wife of his is finally driving him nutso.

145
00:07:56,664 --> 00:08:00,647
Yes, we Crane boys sure know how to marry.

146
00:08:04,705 --> 00:08:06,845
Let me get you a beer, dad.

147
00:08:07,605 --> 00:08:10,848
So, ah, what do you think of what I've done with the place, eh?

148
00:08:10,849 --> 00:08:13,536
You know, every item has been carefully selected.

149
00:08:13,537 --> 00:08:16,170
This lamp by Corbusier, the chair by Eames,

150
00:08:16,171 --> 00:08:21,486
and this couch is an exact replica of the one Coco Chanel had in her Paris atelier.

151
00:08:21,487 --> 00:08:22,989
Nothing matches.

152
00:08:22,990 --> 00:08:24,721
Well, it's a , it's a style of decorating.

153
00:08:24,722 --> 00:08:26,373
it's called "eclectic".

154
00:08:27,719 --> 00:08:28,847
Well, the theory behind it is,

155
00:08:28,848 --> 00:08:32,538
if you've got really fine pieces of furniture, it doesn't matter if they match

156
00:08:32,539 --> 00:08:34,400
They will go together.

157
00:08:35,285 --> 00:08:36,463
It's your money.

158
00:08:40,643 --> 00:08:41,743
Dad, what do you think of the view?

159
00:08:41,744 --> 00:08:43,601
Hey, that's the Space Needle there!

160
00:08:43,602 --> 00:08:44,842
Oh, thanks for pointing that out.

161
00:08:44,843 --> 00:08:47,176
Being born and raised here, I never would have known.

162
00:08:51,185 --> 00:08:52,535
Delivery for Martin Crane.

163
00:08:52,536 --> 00:08:54,336
- Oh, in here!
- Coming through!

164
00:08:54,337 --> 00:08:56,445
Excuse me, excuse me, wait a minute

165
00:08:56,446 --> 00:08:58,617
- Where d'you want it?
- Where's the TV?

166
00:08:58,618 --> 00:09:01,514
- It's in that credenza.
- Point it at that thing.

167
00:09:01,515 --> 00:09:02,619
What about this chair?

168
00:09:02,620 --> 00:09:04,724
Ah, the chair? Here, let me get it out of your way.

169
00:09:04,725 --> 00:09:06,614
Niles, Niles, Niles, be careful with that, that's a Wassily!

170
00:09:08,195 --> 00:09:11,899
Oh, look, dad, as dear as I'm sure this, this peace is to you I,

171
00:09:11,900 --> 00:09:14,663
I just don't think it goes with anything here!

172
00:09:14,664 --> 00:09:16,569
I know, it's eclectic!

173
00:09:20,483 --> 00:09:22,579
Niles, Niles, will you help me out here?

174
00:09:22,580 --> 00:09:24,823
Ah, you're gonna have to run an extension cord over here so

175
00:09:24,824 --> 00:09:26,792
I can plug in the vibrating part.

176
00:09:26,919 --> 00:09:29,734
Oh yes, that will be the crowning touch.

177
00:09:34,046 --> 00:09:36,209
Well, now that you two are settled in, I've got to run.

178
00:09:36,210 --> 00:09:38,729
I'm late for my dysfunctional family seminar.

179
00:09:40,871 --> 00:09:43,259
Dad, have you mentioned Eddie yet?

180
00:09:43,893 --> 00:09:45,777
- Eddie?
- Ta-ta!

181
00:09:46,410 --> 00:09:48,142
Oh, no, dad, no, no! Not Eddie!

182
00:09:48,143 --> 00:09:50,471
But he's my best friend! Get me my beer, would you?

183
00:09:50,472 --> 00:09:51,803
But he's weird!

184
00:09:53,007 --> 00:09:56,020
He gives me the creeps! All he does is stare at me.

185
00:09:56,021 --> 00:09:58,234
- Ah, it's just your imagination.
- No dad, no!

186
00:09:58,235 --> 00:10:02,567
No, I'm sorry, but I am putting my foot down. Eddie is NOT moving in here.

187
00:10:24,555 --> 00:10:27,405
Niles, there you are! I'm sorry I'm late

188
00:10:27,406 --> 00:10:31,629
just as I was leaving, dad decided to cook lunch by the glow of a small kitchen fire!

189
00:10:32,935 --> 00:10:36,329
Oh Niles, this last week with dad, it's, it's been a living hell!

190
00:10:36,330 --> 00:10:38,727
When I'm there, I feel like my territory's being violated

191
00:10:38,728 --> 00:10:40,381
when I'm not, I'm worried about what he's up to.

192
00:10:40,906 --> 00:10:42,665
Look at me, look at me, I'm a nervous wreck!

193
00:10:42,666 --> 00:10:45,079
I've got to do something to calm down. Double espresso, please!

194
00:10:46,472 --> 00:10:50,810
Niles, you don't still have the brochures from those rest homes, do you?

195
00:10:50,811 --> 00:10:51,690
Of course I do.

196
00:10:51,691 --> 00:10:53,915
Don't forget, Maris is five years older than I am.

197
00:10:58,480 --> 00:11:00,200
But you really think that's necessary?

198
00:11:00,959 --> 00:11:01,888
I'm afraid I do.

199
00:11:02,582 --> 00:11:04,159
I don't have my life anymore.

200
00:11:04,664 --> 00:11:07,993
Tuesday night I gave up my tickets to the theatre, Wednesday it was the symphony...

201
00:11:07,994 --> 00:11:09,860
That reminds me, weren't you going to the opera on Friday?

202
00:11:09,861 --> 00:11:11,352
- Yes, here.
- Thank you.

203
00:11:14,778 --> 00:11:20,118
Niles, you don't suppose there's a chance that you and Maris could...

204
00:11:20,119 --> 00:11:21,201
Funny you should mention that.

205
00:11:21,202 --> 00:11:23,313
Maris and I were just discussing this.

206
00:11:23,314 --> 00:11:26,256
We feel we should do more to share the responsibility.

207
00:11:26,257 --> 00:11:27,593
You mean you'd take him in?

208
00:11:28,027 --> 00:11:28,594
Dear God, no!

209
00:11:31,802 --> 00:11:34,607
But we would be willing to help you pay for a home care worker.

210
00:11:34,608 --> 00:11:35,563
- A what?

211
00:11:35,564 --> 00:11:38,698
You know, someone who cooks and cleans and can help dad with his physical theraphy.

212
00:11:39,059 --> 00:11:40,907
These angels exist?

213
00:11:41,731 --> 00:11:42,870
I know of an agency

214
00:11:42,871 --> 00:11:45,425
let me arrange for them to send a few people over to meet with you.

215
00:11:46,752 --> 00:11:49,646
Niles, I can't thank you enough!

216
00:11:49,647 --> 00:11:52,700
I, I, I fell this overwhelming urge to hug you!

217
00:11:52,905 --> 00:11:54,057
Remember what Mom always said:

218
00:11:54,361 --> 00:11:55,775
"A handshake is as good as a hug."

219
00:11:58,531 --> 00:12:00,196
Wise woman.

220
00:12:00,900 --> 00:12:05,841
I have never been more impressed with a human being in my life!

221
00:12:07,484 --> 00:12:09,149
Now what was wrong with that one?!

222
00:12:10,661 --> 00:12:12,224
She was casing the joint.

223
00:12:12,514 --> 00:12:13,999
"Casing the joint!"

224
00:12:14,556 --> 00:12:16,528
She spent two years with Mother Teresa!

225
00:12:17,842 --> 00:12:20,257
Well, if I were Mother Teresa, I'd check my jewellery box!

226
00:12:24,185 --> 00:12:27,721
Oh, this is the last one. Can you please try to keep an open mind?

227
00:12:29,358 --> 00:12:33,041
Oh! Hello - caught me with my hand in the biscuit tin!

228
00:12:33,988 --> 00:12:36,023
I'm Daphne, Daphne Moon.

229
00:12:36,273 --> 00:12:38,119
- Frasier Crane. Please come in.
- Thank you.

230
00:12:38,120 --> 00:12:42,156
Eh, this is my father, Martin Crane. Dad, this is Daphne Moon.

231
00:12:42,157 --> 00:12:43,462
Nice to meet you.

232
00:12:44,144 --> 00:12:45,803
Oh, and who might this be?

233
00:12:46,541 --> 00:12:47,847
That is Eddie.

234
00:12:52,901 --> 00:12:54,236
I call him "Eddie Spaghetti".

235
00:12:54,237 --> 00:12:55,805
Oh, he likes pasta?

236
00:12:55,806 --> 00:12:57,200
No, he has worms.

237
00:13:01,754 --> 00:13:04,772
Er, have a seat, Miss Moon.

238
00:13:04,773 --> 00:13:06,673
Daphne. Thank you.

239
00:13:08,281 --> 00:13:12,392
Oh, will you look at that. What a comfy chair!

240
00:13:12,393 --> 00:13:14,263
It's like I always say,

241
00:13:14,264 --> 00:13:18,201
start with a good piece and replace the rest when you can afford it.

242
00:13:25,636 --> 00:13:27,378
Yes. Well, er,

243
00:13:27,379 --> 00:13:30,194
perhaps you should start by telling us a little bit about yourself, Miss Moon.

244
00:13:30,470 --> 00:13:33,516
Well, I'm originally from Manchester, England...

245
00:13:33,517 --> 00:13:34,668
Oh really, did you hear that dad?

246
00:13:34,669 --> 00:13:36,976
I'm three feet away. There's nothing wrong with my hearing.

247
00:13:40,512 --> 00:13:43,419
I've only been in the U.S. for a few months,

